<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=73 g=1 f=1 -->
6. Time and Temperature Critical Control 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Points 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=71 g=1 f=1 -->
a. Cooling After Cooking 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
After cooking, the product must be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
rapidly cooled to minimize recontamination. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Continuous cooling from 140 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;F (60 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;C) to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
achieve an internal temperature of 70 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;F 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(21.1 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;C) or below within 2 hours and an 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
internal temperature of 40 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;F (4.4 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;C) or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
below within an additional 4 hours, unless 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
processing after cooking, as described in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
section 6.b. of this Appendix, occurs during 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
either of these time periods, will 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
effectively minimize recontamination. Other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
time/temperature parameters may also be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
effective. Processors should ensure that the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cooling parameters are met by either: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 1. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Monitoring.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 Monitoring and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
recording internal product temperatures at 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
least every 2 hours; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 2. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Studies. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 i. Conducting or obtaining a study that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
establishes that appropriate cooling 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
temperatures are always met under prescribed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
processing conditions. The study should 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
establish the limits of significant variables 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that could affect the rate of cooling. These 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
variables may include product size, ambient 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
air temperature, and amount of product in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cooler. An adequate study should consist of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
at least three processing runs under the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
prescribed processing conditions; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 ii. Monitoring and recording the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
prescribed processing conditions as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
identified by the study in section 6.a.2.i. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of this Appendix at least every 2 hours. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=71 g=1 f=3 -->
b. Processing After Cooking 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Products that will receive processing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
after cooking should not be exposed to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
ambient temperatures of 40 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;F (4.4 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;C) or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
higher for longer than a cumulative total of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4 hours after cooking. If they are exposed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to such temperatures for more than 4 hours, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
unacceptable recontamination is the likely 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
result. Processors are required to regularly 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
monitor and record the length of time that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the product is exposed to temperatures above 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
40 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;F (4.4 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;C) under 21 CFR 123.8. FDA 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
recommends that such monitoring and recording 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
be done at least every 2 hours. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=71 g=1 f=3 -->
c. Final Product Cooling 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
To avoid microbiological hazards for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
perishable finished products, the internal 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
temperature of the finished product should be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
40 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;F (4.4 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;C) or below within 4 hours of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
either placement in a finished product 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
container or the completion of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
pasteurization. Processors should either 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
conduct: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 1. Monitoring.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 Monitor and record 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
internal product temperatures at least every 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2 hours; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 2. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Studies. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 i. Conduct or obtain a study that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
establishes that the internal temperature of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the finished product will always be 40 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;F 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4.4 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;C) or below within 4 hours of either 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
placement in a finished product container or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
completion of pasteurization under prescribed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
processing conditions. The study should 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
establish the limits of significant variables 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that could affect the rate of cooling. These 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
variables may include product size, ambient 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
air temperature, and amount of product in the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cooler. An adequate study should consist of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
at least three processing runs under the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
prescribed processing conditions; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 ii. Monitoring and recording the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
prescribed processing conditions as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
identified by the study in section 6.c.2.i. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of this Appendix at least every 2 hours. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=71 g=1 f=3 -->
d. Refrigerated Storage
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
1. In-process products.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 Refrigeration 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
units that are being used to store in-process 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
products or finished products shall operate 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
at a temperature of 40 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
&cir;F (4.4 
<!-- PJG 0040 degreeslatlong -->
